When I say: “A or B is the first boy in the class”, “First boy in the class’' belongs to A or to 133 we know not to which of the two, yet we know that it belongs distinctly to one, excluding the other. This is a higher form of inherence, since the vagueness is only in our thought, not in the fact. The lowest of these forms, being the least perceptible‚ has been denied by some, who are too deeply plunged in the senses to perceive it. The highest is when a Universal is affirmed of many together: as, “All men are mortal‘³. “Mortal'’ belongs to each man separately and to the whole multitude of singular men together. The cavils of our opponents proceed from their not distinguishing between these various sorts of inherence, and are answered victoriously by means of this distinction (p. 118, l. 20 to end of chapter).
